\ud3f4\ud0b4), CHUNG HA(\uccad\ud558) _ Loveship |author=YouTube|publisher=MNH Entertainment|date=January 21, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Everybody Has\" {{small|({{lang|ko|\uc194\uc9c1\ud788 \uc9c0\uce5c\ub2e4}})}}\n| ''[[New.wav]]''\n| VISHOP </br>(Vikings League)\n| <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://m.app.melon.com/album/detail.htm?albumId=10396024|title=\uc194\uc9c1\ud788 \uc9c0\uce5c\ub2e4.newwav|first=|last=|date=February 29, 2020|work=melon.com|language=Korean|accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Songwriting credits==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\" \n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:2em;\" |Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:7em;\" |Album\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:13em;\" |Song\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\" |Lyrics\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\" |Music\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\" |Arrangement\n|-\n!style=\"width:4em;\" |Credited\n!style=\"width:13em;\" |With\n!style=\"width:4em;\" |Credited\n!style=\"width:8em;\" |With\n!style=\"width:4em;\" |Credited\n!style=\"width:8em;\" |With\n|-\n| rowspan=1|2017\n| rowspan=1|''[[Hands on Me (EP)|Hands on Me]]''\n| \"Hands on Me\"\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{small|VINCENZO, Fuxxy, Any Masingga}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{NA}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{NA}}\n|-\n| rowspan=1|2018\n| rowspan=1|''[[Offset (EP)|Offset]]''\n| \"Offset\"\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{small|VINCENZO, Fuxxy, Any Masingga}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{NA}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{NA}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2019\n| rowspan=1|''[[Flourishing (EP)|Flourishing]]''\n| \"Flourishing\"\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{small|Anna Timgren, VINCENZO}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{small|Anna Timgren, VINCENZO}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{NA}}\n|-\n| rowspan=1|''[[Head in the Clouds II]]''\n| \"These Nights\"\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{small|Slanger, Montana Wayne Best, McCulloch Reid Sutphin, Jordan Orvosh, Rich Brian}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{NA}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{NA}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[I.O.I discography]]\n* [[List of songs recorded by Chungha]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Chungha}}\n\n[[Category:Discographies of South Korean artists]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 -WP:WCWproject (Tag with incorrect syntax)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chungha_discography"}
{"title_page": "Capital Airlines Flight 300", "text_new": "{{short description|1958 aviation accident}}\n{{Infobox Aircraft accident\n|name = Capital Airlines Flight 300 \n|image = Capital Airlines Flight 300 (2).jpg\n|caption = Forward section of the Vickers Viscount\n|date = {{start-date|May 20, 1958}}\n|type = [[Mid-air collision]]\n|occurrence_type = Accident\n|site = Four miles east-northeast of [[Brunswick, Maryland]] \n|coords = {{coord|39|18|39.71|N|77|37|7.95|W|region:US-MD_type:event|display=inline,title}}\n|total_injuries = 1\n|total_fatalities = 12\n|total_survivors = 1 \n|plane1_image = G-arir.jpg\n|plane1_caption = A Vickers Viscount similar to the one involved in the incident.\n|plane1_type = [[Vickers Viscount]]\n|plane1_name =\n|plane1_operator = Capital Airlines \n|plane1_tailnum = [https://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19580520-1 N7410]\n|plane1_passengers = 7\n|plane1_crew = 4\n|plane1_survivors = 0\n|plane2_image = Lockheed NT-33A USAF.jpg\n|plane2_caption = A T-33 Shooting Star similar to the one involved in the incident.\n|plane2_type = [[Lockheed T-33]]\n|plane2_name =\n|plane2_operator = USAF Maryland Air National Guard\n|plane2_tailnum = [http://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=189007 53-5966]\n|plane2_passengers = \n|plane2_crew = 2\n|plane2_survivors = 1\n}}\nOn May 20, 1958 a [[Vickers Viscount]] airliner operating '''Capital Airlines Flight 300''' was involved in a [[mid air collision]] with a USAF [[T-33]] [[Trainer (aircraft)|jet trainer]] on a proficiency flight in the skies above [[Brunswick, Maryland]]. All 11 people on board the Viscount and one of the two crew in the T-33 were killed in the accident. Flight 300 was the second of four fatal crashes in the space of two years involving Capital Airlines [[Vickers Viscount]]s; the other were [[Capital Airlines Flight 67]] (April 1958) [[Capital Airlines Flight 75]] (May 1959) and [[Capital Airlines Flight 20]] (January 1960).\n\nAn investigation of the accident concluded that the [[pilot in command]] of the T-33 failed to see and maintain a safe distance from other air traffic. \n\n==Accident==\n[[Capital Airlines (United States)|Capital Airlines]] Flight 300 was a regular scheduled flight from [[Chicago, Illinois]] to [[Baltimore, Maryland]] with an intermediate stop at [[Pittsburgh,  Pennsylvania]]. The flight from Chicago was uneventful and at 10:50 local time the airliner departed Pittsburgh bound for Baltimore. At 11:25 while cruising  at 11,000 feet Washington Air Traffic Control cleared Flight 300 to descend and maintain 7,000 feet. At 11:26 the Viscount crew reported descending through 10,000 feet over Martinsburg and radar contact was made by ATC. 48 seconds later flight 300 reported leaving 9,000 feet with clearance to 5,000 feet. This was the last radio transmission from the Viscount.<ref name=bae>{{cite web |url=http://www.baesel.net/capaccidents/1958.05.20_CapitalAirlines_Viscount&MarylandAirNationalGuard_T33.pdf\n|title=Aircraft Accident Report|author=|date=January 9, 1959 |website=www.baesel.net|publisher=CIVIL AERONAUTICS BOARD|access-date=16 April 2018}}</ref>\n      \nThe T-33 jet trainer launched from [[Martin State Airport]] at 11:07 for a VFR familiarization flight. The T-33's air speed was significantly higher as it approached the Viscount from the left and behind. The Viscounts indicated air speed was 235 knots while the T-33's was 290 knots with a closing rate of approximately 195 knots. While slowly climbing through 8,000 feet at 85 percent engine power the jet banked slightly to the right and impacted the left side of the airliner forward of the wing. The airliner pitched up, its air speed decreasing, then the nose dropped and the aircraft entered a steep spin to the right, slowing to a flat spin before it struck the ground. The T-33 pilot was thrown clear of the flaming jet and parachuted safely to the ground but was badly burned. The jet disintegrated after the collision and the passenger was fatally injured.<ref name=bae/><ref name=asn>{{cite web |url=https://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19580520-1\n|title=Accident description|author=|date= 2018|website=aviation-safety.net|publisher=Aviation Safety Network (ASN)|access-date=16 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=vic>{{cite web |url=http://www.vickersviscount.net/Index/VickersViscount108History.aspx\n|title=Viscount c/n 108 |author=Geoff Blampied|date=2018|website=www.vickersviscount.net|publisher=Vickers Viscount Network|access-date=16 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Aircraft and crew==\n\n=== Vickers aircraft and crew ===\nThe four engine Viscount V.745 British medium-range [[turboprop]] [[airliner]], serial number 108, first flew from Hampshire, England on 6 January, 1956. Powered by [[Rolls-Royce Dart|Rolls-Royce Dart RDa3 Mark 506]] engines turning four blade square tipped [[constant-speed propeller|constant-speed propellers]], it was delivered to Capital Airlines on 15 January, 1956 as fleet number 329.<ref name=bae/>\n\nThe pilot in command of Flight 300 was Captain Kendall Brady, age 38. He had a valid airman certificate and was rated to fly single/multi-engine land aircraft as well as the Douglas DC-3, DC-4 and the Vickers Viscount. Brady's total flying hours were 12,719 with 1,432 of those in the Viscount. He was hired by Capital Airlines on 11 June, 1945.<ref name=bae/>\n\nPaul Meyer, age 26, served as co-pilot and started flying for Capital Airlines on 25 May, 1956. He was certified to operate single/multi-engine land aircraft and had an instrument rating. Meyer's total flight hours were 2,467, of which 1,596 were in the Viscount.<ref name=bae/>\n\n=== T-33 aircraft and crew ===\nThe two-place Lockheed T-33A Shooting Star subsonic American jet trainer aircraft involved was manufacture serial number 580-9528 and registered 53-5966. It was maintained by the Maryland Air National Guard and equipped with an [[Allison J33|Allison J33-A-35]] turbojet engine.<ref name=bae/>\n\nThe pilot and sole survivor of the accident was Captain Julius  McCoy, age 34. He was rated as a military pilot August 4, 1944 and joined the Maryland Air National Guard in 1952. He had a total of 1,902 hours in single- and multi-engine and single-engine jet aircraft 210 were in the T-33.<ref name=bae/>\n\n==Investigation==\nThe [[Civil Aeronautics Board]] (CAB) investigated the accident and released a report on January 9, 1959. It detrimined that the collision happened during [[visual flight rules|VFR]] conditions and that both aircraft would have been in clear cloud free air nine-tenths of the time. The report noted that it is the overtaking aircraft's responsibility to see and avoid a collision. A contributing factor in the accident was that the small size of the T-33 made it difficult to pick up on radar. The board attributed no blame to the Viscount crew and stated in conclusion that \"The Board determines the probable cause of this accident was the failure of the T-33 pilot to exercise a proper and adequate vigilance to see and avoid other traffic.\"<ref name=bae/>\n\n\n==See also==\n*[[Eastern Air Lines Flight 45]]\n*[[1958 in aviation]]\n*[[List of accidents and incidents on commercial aircraft]]\n*[[Mid-air collision]] - includes a list of other notable mid-air collisions.\n\n{{Portal|Aviation}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in 1958}}\n\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in 1958]]\n[[Category:Airliner accidents and incidents involving mid-air collisions]]\n[[Category:Mid-air collisions]]\n[[Category:May 1958 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1958 aviation accident}}\n{{Infobox Aircraft accident\n|name = Capital Airlines Flight 300 \n|image = Capital Airlines Flight 300 (2).jpg\n|caption = Forward section of the Vickers Viscount\n|date = {{start-date|May 20, 1958}}\n|type = [[Mid-air collision]]\n|occurrence_type = Accident\n|site = Four miles east-northeast of [[Brunswick, Maryland]] \n|coords = {{coord|39|18|39.71|N|77|37|7.95|W|region:US-MD_type:event|display=inline,title}}\n|total_injuries = 1\n|total_fatalities = 12\n|total_survivors = 1 \n|plane1_image = G-arir.jpg\n|plane1_caption = A Vickers Viscount similar to the one involved in the incident.\n|plane1_type = [[Vickers Viscount]]\n|plane1_name =\n|plane1_operator = Capital Airlines \n|plane1_tailnum = [https://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19580520-1 N7410]\n|plane1_passengers = 7\n|plane1_crew = 4\n|plane1_survivors = 0\n|plane2_image = Lockheed NT-33A USAF.jpg\n|plane2_caption = A T-33 Shooting Star similar to the one involved in the incident.\n|plane2_type = [[Lockheed T-33]]\n|plane2_name =\n|plane2_operator = USAF Maryland Air National Guard\n|plane2_tailnum = [http://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=189007 53-5966]\n|plane2_passengers = \n|plane2_crew = 2\n|plane2_survivors = 1\n}}\nOn May 20, 1958 a [[Vickers Viscount]] airliner operating '''Capital Airlines Flight 300''' was involved in a [[mid air collision]] with a USAF [[T-33]] [[Trainer (aircraft)|jet trainer]] on a proficiency flight in the skies above [[Brunswick, Maryland]]. All 11 people on board the Viscount and one of the two crew in the T-33 were killed in the accident. Flight 300 was the second of four fatal crashes in the space of two years involving Capital Airlines [[Vickers Viscount]]s; the other were [[Capital Airlines Flight 67]] (April 1958) [[Capital Airlines Flight 75]] (May 1959) and [[Capital Airlines Flight 20]] (January 1960).\n\nAn investigation of the accident concluded that the [[pilot in command]] of the T-33 failed see and maintain a safe distance from other air traffic. \n\n==Accident==\n[[Capital Airlines (United States)|Capital Airlines]] Flight 300 was a regular scheduled flight from [[Chicago, Illinois]] to [[Baltimore, Maryland]] with an intermediate stop at [[Pittsburgh,  Pennsylvania]]. The flight from Chicago was uneventful and at 10:50 local time the airliner departed Pittsburgh bound for Baltimore. At 11:25 while cruising  at 11,000 feet Washington Air Traffic Control cleared Flight 300 to descend and maintain 7,000 feet. At 11:26 the Viscount crew reported descending through 10,000 feet over Martinsburg and radar contact was made by ATC. 48 seconds later flight 300 reported leaving 9,000 feet with clearance to 5,000 feet. This was the last radio transmission from the Viscount.<ref name=bae>{{cite web |url=http://www.baesel.net/capaccidents/1958.05.20_CapitalAirlines_Viscount&MarylandAirNationalGuard_T33.pdf\n|title=Aircraft Accident Report|author=|date=January 9, 1959 |website=www.baesel.net|publisher=CIVIL AERONAUTICS BOARD|access-date=16 April 2018}}</ref>\n      \nThe T-33 jet trainer launched from [[Martin State Airport]] at 11:07 for a VFR familiarization flight. The T-33's air speed was significantly higher as it approached the Viscount from the left and behind. The Viscounts indicated air speed was 235 knots while the T-33's was 290 knots with a closing rate of approximately 195 knots. While slowly climbing through 8,000 feet at 85 percent engine power the jet banked slightly to the right and impacted the left side of the airliner forward of the wing. The airliner pitched up, its air speed decreasing, then the nose dropped and the aircraft entered a steep spin to the right, slowing to a flat spin before it struck the ground. The T-33 pilot was thrown clear of the flaming jet and parachuted safely to the ground but was badly burned. The jet disintegrated after the collision and the passenger was fatally injured.<ref name=bae/><ref name=asn>{{cite web |url=https://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19580520-1\n|title=Accident description|author=|date= 2018|website=aviation-safety.net|publisher=Aviation Safety Network (ASN)|access-date=16 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=vic>{{cite web |url=http://www.vickersviscount.net/Index/VickersViscount108History.aspx\n|title=Viscount c/n 108 |author=Geoff Blampied|date=2018|website=www.vickersviscount.net|publisher=Vickers Viscount Network|access-date=16 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Aircraft and crew==\n\n=== Vickers aircraft and crew ===\nThe four engine Viscount V.745 British medium-range [[turboprop]] [[airliner]], serial number 108, first flew from Hampshire, England on 6 January, 1956. Powered by [[Rolls-Royce Dart|Rolls-Royce Dart RDa3 Mark 506]] engines turning four blade square tipped [[constant-speed propeller|constant-speed propellers]], it was delivered to Capital Airlines on 15 January, 1956 as fleet number 329.<ref name=bae/>\n\nThe pilot in command of Flight 300 was Captain Kendall Brady, age 38. He had a valid airman certificate and was rated to fly single/multi-engine land aircraft as well as the Douglas DC-3, DC-4 and the Vickers Viscount. Brady's total flying hours were 12,719 with 1,432 of those in the Viscount. He was hired by Capital Airlines on 11 June, 1945.<ref name=bae/>\n\nPaul Meyer, age 26, served as co-pilot and started flying for Capital Airlines on 25 May, 1956. He was certified to operate single/multi-engine land aircraft and had an instrument rating. Meyer's total flight hours were 2,467, of which 1,596 were in the Viscount.<ref name=bae/>\n\n=== T-33 aircraft and crew ===\nThe two-place Lockheed T-33A Shooting Star subsonic American jet trainer aircraft involved was manufacture serial number 580-9528 and registered 53-5966. It was maintained by the Maryland Air National Guard and equipped with an [[Allison J33|Allison J33-A-35]] turbojet engine.<ref name=bae/>\n\nThe pilot and sole survivor of the accident was Captain Julius  McCoy, age 34. He was rated as a military pilot August 4, 1944 and joined the Maryland Air National Guard in 1952. He had a total of 1,902 hours in single- and multi-engine and single-engine jet aircraft 210 were in the T-33.<ref name=bae/>\n\n==Investigation==\nThe [[Civil Aeronautics Board]] (CAB) investigated the accident and released a report on January 9, 1959. It detrimined that the collision happened during [[visual flight rules|VFR]] conditions and that both aircraft would have been in clear cloud free air nine-tenths of the time. The report noted that it is the overtaking aircraft's responsibility to see and avoid a collision. A contributing factor in the accident was that the small size of the T-33 made it difficult to pick up on radar. The board attributed no blame to the Viscount crew and stated in conclusion that \"The Board determines the probable cause of this accident was the failure of the T-33 pilot to exercise a proper and adequate vigilance to see and avoid other traffic.\"<ref name=bae/>\n\n\n==See also==\n*[[Eastern Air Lines Flight 45]]\n*[[1958 in aviation]]\n*[[List of accidents and incidents on commercial aircraft]]\n*[[Mid-air collision]] - includes a list of other notable mid-air collisions.\n\n{{Portal|Aviation}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in 1958}}\n\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in 1958]]\n[[Category:Airliner accidents and incidents involving mid-air collisions]]\n[[Category:Mid-air collisions]]\n[[Category:May 1958 events]]\n", "name_user": "Cathartid", "label": "safe", "comment": "add missing \"to\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_Airlines_Flight_300"}
{"title_page": "Vumomse", "text_new": "{{short description|Cameroonian musician and songwriter}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| background      = solo_singer\n| alias           = Vumomse\n| birth_name      = Charles Vumomse\n| genre           = [[Gospel]] [[Afro pop]] [[Inspirational music|Inspiration]]\n| landscape       = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| occupation      = [[Musician]]\n| years_active    = 2012\u2013present\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n*[[Tim Godfrey]]\n*[[Mokambe]]\n*[[Kingzkid]]\n}}\n| image           = Vumomse.jpg\n}}\n'''Charles Vumomse''' better known as '''Vumomse''' is a Cameroonian Afro-pop and urban [[gospel musician]] and songwriter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.camerounweb.com/CameroonHomePage/entertainment/Interview-US-based-Cameroonian-gospel-artist-Charles-Vumomse-314577|title=Interview: US-based Cameroonian gospel artist Charles Vumomse|website=www.camerounweb.com|language=fr|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/Gospel-singer-Vumomse-drops-new-single-Shine-Everyday-890257|title=Gospel singer Vumomse drops new single 'Shine Everyday'|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gospelhypers.com/2020/03/gospel-artist-profile-vumomse.html|title=Gospel Artist Profile - Vumoms\u00e9 - Gospel Hypers - Gospel Music Marketing And Entertainment Hub|website=www.gospelhypers.com|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nVumomse is a family nurse [[Health practitioner|practitioner]] and an alumnus of [[South University]], Georgia, United States with a [[Masters Degree]]. He is married to Peace Favor with whom they have four children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missginapromotes.com/charles-vumomse-celebrate-10th-wedding-anniversary/|title=Charles Vumomse and Wife Celebrate 10th Wedding Anniversary|last=admin|date=2018-10-11|website=Miss Gina Promotes|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n== Music career ==\nVomomse released his first album Rakata in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.camerounweb.com/CameroonHomePage/entertainment/Acclaimed-dancer-prepares-stage-for-maiden-gospel-album-315158|title=Acclaimed dancer prepares stage for maiden gospel album|website=www.camerounweb.com|language=fr|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> which earned him a nomination at the All Africa Music Award [[AFRIMA|'AFRIMA']].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allafrica.com/view/group/main/main/id/00038483.html|title=Nominees for the All Africa Music Awards Unveiled|date=2015-08-25|website=allAfrica.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> He is the [[Co-Founder|Co Founder]] of Calabash Music Label and the and Host of ''Solid Rock Worship Festival'' an annual worship concert which aims at winning souls for the Kingdom of God. Vumomse has performed and worked with many African Gospel Artiste including, [[Tim Godfrey (musician)|Tim Godfrey]], [[Mercy Chinwo]], Uche Agu, Mokambe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.africanhitz.com/video-audio-vumomse-man-made-god-ft-mokambe-vumomseofficial/|title=Video + Audio: Vumomse - Man Made God (ft. Mokambe) @VumomseOfficial|last=Dee|first=Mod|date=2017-09-15|website=Africanhitz|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.musicinafrica.net/magazine/afrima-announces-first-batch-nominees-2015|title=AFRIMA announces first batch of nominees for 2015|date=2015-08-18|website=Music In Africa|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Album ===\n\n* Rakata (2014)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/rakata-mw0002833260|title=Rakata - Vumomse {{!}} User Reviews|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stelladimokokorkus.com/2015/01/rakata-by-vumomse.html|title=RAKATA by Vumoms\u00e9|last=Korkus|first=Stella Dimoko|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n==== Selected singles ====\n\n* Shine Everyday<ref>{{Cite